“The Foraging Pen”: A video by Mai Li O’Barry
Our team has been feeding the dolphins as many live fish as possible every day. The fishermen assigned to the dolphin rehabilitation project arrive during the night with lots of fresh live fish. They load the fish into the “foraging pen,” which has mesh the fish cannot swim through. It is separated from the other sea pens with a gate that we open each morning. The dolphins zoom into the foraging pen as quickly as they can, and the chase begins.
Learn more about the Umah Lumba Rehabilitatopn, Release and Retirement Center by going to DolphinProject.com

(Graphic Footage) Yesterday, Jan. 14, 2021, a pod of striped dolphins was driven into the cove. The pod went into a panic, with several individuals crashing into rocks and getting entangled in nets. The water turned bright red, as they bled from injuries. As documented countless time before, this footage reinforces prolonged suffering, and incredibly inhumane aspects of this hunt. After the hunters were able to wrestle the dolphins under the tarps, the entire pod was slaughtered. Don’t let this horrific event be forgotten. Contact authorities in the captivity industry and in the Japanese government and urge them to put an end to this. Find calls to action at DolphinProject.com

node.text:
Over the course of a 3 day long brutal captive selection process, 85 bottlenose dolphins have been taken into captivity from an extremely large pod that was netted in the cove for 4 days, with no access to food. At least one captured dolphin has died during this process. After captive selection, the remaining, exhausted pod was driven out to sea.
These horrific captures happen every year because there continues to be demand from the world's dolphinariums. As long as the dolphin show business model remains profitable, hunts like this are likely to continue. France and Canada have recently joined the list of countries that are phasing out cetacean captivity. It's up to all of us to continue taking action to end the global demand for captive dolphins. Find calls to action by going to: dolphin.fyi/HelpJapanDolphins

node.text:
On Dec. 7, 2020 a pod of melon-headed whales was driven into the cove in Taiji, Japan. Despite claims of these hunting methods being “humane,” there is major cause for concern of the suffering these animals endure throughout the hunting process. During this hunt, one melon-headed whale was seen with flukes tethered to a skiff- this tethering method is typically used after the cetacean has been killed and is being towed back to the harbor. Many other individuals swam into the nets in panic, and appeared to be struggling to surface. Approximately 18 melon-headed whales were slaughtered in this hunt. Please help us tell their story. Go to DolphinProject.com and click on our Taiji campaign to learn more and how you can help.
Footage by: @life_investigation_agency

On Dec. 2, 2020 a large pod of melon-headed whales was driven into the Cove in Taiji. As depicted in this footage, the pod endured panic and distress. Several of them swam into nets and rocks in desperate attempts at escape. The hunters did not slaughter the entire pod, yet the bodies of those that were slaughtered were dragged out right next to the surviving pod members. 
It's important to keep in mind that these drive hunts are kept profiteable through selling the dolphins that arecaptured alive to aquariums and marine parks. If the demand for captive cetaceans ends, demand for the hunts ends, too. Help be a voice for these cetaceans and take action: dolphin.fyi/HelpJapanDolphins (case sensitive)

UPDATE: The whale has been released! Around 9:00 AM this morning (Nov. 30), fishing boats came to pull up some of the nets, and the whale was able to swim out to sea. 

From @life_investigation_agency :
Yesterday, a humpback whale was sighted trapped in fishing nets outside of the Taiji harbor. At the time of the initial sighting (seen here), the whale was not entangled, but had swam into an area of nets and appeared unable to get out. The Life Investigation Agency team and Japanese activists contacted the party responsible for the fishing nets, but they stated they would try to open the next the next day (today). This morning, the whale has been re-sighted, still swimming inside of the netted area. In addition to monitoring the drive hunt today, our collaborative team will continue to monitor the whale as much as possible.
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
On Friday, the dolphin hunting fleet in Taiji spent hours on high-power vessels searching for and driving in a small pod of 3 Risso's dolphins. All 3 were slaughtered in the cove. Taiji's dolphin hunts are ultimately kept profitable by the dolphins that are captured alive, and sold to marine parks and aquariums. If the demand for captive dolphin displays ends, the demand for the hunts ends, too. Help spread the word and take action at: dolphin.fyi/HelpJapanDolphins
.
Footage by @life_investigation_agency 
Coverage in Taiji this season is in collaboration with Japanese activists at Life Investigation Agency
.
.
.
.
.

node.text: Concerning footage from our collaborators at @life_investigation_agency from the melon-headed whale drive on Nov. 2, 2020. One melon-headed whale is caught in an orange net for several minutes, seemingly ignored by the hunters. Meanwhile, other melon-headed whales are grabbed and taken to the tarped area for slaughter one after another. There are also bloody wounds on the rostrum area on several individuals. Despite claims of “humane” killing methods used in these hunts, it is clear that these cetaceans endure extremely concerning conditions before they are slaughtered.

node.title: Melon-Headed Whales Hunted in Taiji - Nov. 2, 2020

node.text:
Havok, one of five beluga whales brought to Mystic Aquarium from Canada in May has died. ⁠
An article from The Day reports, "he arrived with four female belugas from Marineland in Niagara Falls, Canada, the approximately 6-year-old whale was brought in as part of a non-invasive research program at the aquarium meant to help with wild beluga conservation efforts. Mystic Aquarium in a statement said he died Friday about 6:30 a.m. He was being treated for gastric ulcers developed before arriving and had been showing signs of improvement throughout his acclimation period, according to the aquarium." This article is linked in our bio.

node.text:
Among the issues with dolphin petting pools, sometimes the dolphins are touched in rough or painful ways by well-meaning tourists, potentially introducing pathogens into the water and onto the dolphins’ skin. Inevitably, garbage is dropped in the pool, creating a choking hazard for dolphins. And visitors get injured by the dolphins. Clearly, the regulation of this facility is desperately inadequate, putting both dolphins and humans at risk.⁠
Read more bit.ly/35arpXo (linked in bio).⁠
#DolphinProject
